Introduction

This analysis examines RNA-seq data from matched tumor and normal tissue samples collected from 5 patients, yielding a total of 10 samples. The raw count matrix contains expression data for 19,701 genes across these samples.

Since each patient contributed both a tumor and normal sample, this represents a paired experimental design. This pairing is statistically advantageous because it allows us to control for patient-to-patient variability (due to age, genetics, lifestyle, etc.) and focus on the true biological differences between tumor and normal tissue within each individual.

Analysis Objectives

  1. Implement a complete RNA-seq analysis workflow from raw counts to differential expression results
  2. Visualize normalized gene expression and sample relationships
  3. Identify top differentially expressed genes between tumor and normal groups
  4. Perform Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) to identify dysregulated biological pathways

  }
}

invisible(suppressMessages(suppressWarnings(
  lapply(required_packages, library, character.only = TRUE)
)))

Q1 Output the R workflow you use for the analysis from raw data to generating differential expression results.

library(DESeq2) 
library(dplyr)

# Read in the raw read counts and sample data
rawCounts <- read.delim("/Users/dr.parul/Downloads/assignment files/Data needed for the assignment-20251125/row_count_data.nodup.txt", header = TRUE, row.names = 1)
rawCounts <- ceiling(rawCounts) 
sampleData <- read.delim("/Users/dr.parul/Downloads/assignment files/Data needed for the assignment-20251125/sample_groups.txt", header = TRUE, row.names = 1)

# Prepare Data & Filtering
sampleData <- sampleData[colnames(rawCounts), ]
sampleData$Patient <- factor(sampleData$Patient)
sampleData$Group <- factor(sampleData$Group)
sampleData$Group <- relevel(sampleData$Group, ref = "Normal")

# Create DESeq2 Object & Filter
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = rawCounts, colData = sampleData, design = ~ Patient + Group)
## converting counts to integer mode
keep <- rowSums(counts(dds) >= 10) >= 5
dds <- dds[keep, ]

# Run the DESeq analysis
dds <- DESeq(dds)

##Answer 2b
# B. PCA PLOT OF THE 10 SAMPLES (Question 2b)
# Getting PCA coordinates using VST-transformed counts
pcaData <- plotPCA(vsd, intgroup = c("Group", "Patient"), returnData = TRUE)
## using ntop=500 top features by variance
percentVar <- round(100 * attr(pcaData, "percentVar"))

# Plot PCA with lines connecting paired samples
ggplot(pcaData, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = Group, group = Patient)) +
    geom_point(size = 4, aes(shape = Patient)) +
    geom_line(aes(linetype = Patient), color = "grey50") +
    xlab(paste0("PC1: ", percentVar[1], "% variance")) +
    ylab(paste0("PC2: ", percentVar[2], "% variance")) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("Normal" = "#1f78b4", "Tumour" = "#e31a1c")) +
    theme_minimal() +
    ggtitle("PCA Plot of Samples with Paired Tumour-Normal Connections") +
    theme(legend.position = "right", plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"))

Interpretation:PCA shows clear separation between Normal (blue) and Tumour (red) samples along PC1 (44% variance), indicating distinct gene expression profiles between the two groups. The paired design is visible through connecting lines, with most patients showing consistent NormalTumour shifts toward positive PC1 values. S06 shows the largest difference between paired samples, with S06_Tumour being the most distinct sample (PC1 ~38), consistent with the outlier pattern observed in the boxplot.

## Preparing file to be used later for GSEA with the sigs.df.annot column for gene symbols.
library(org.Hs.eg.db)
## Loading required package: AnnotationDbi
## 
## Attaching package: 'AnnotationDbi'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
## 
# 1. Convert DESeq2 results to data.frame
res.df <- as.data.frame(res)

# 2. Extract gene symbols (rownames)
gene_symbols <- rownames(res.df)

# 3. Map SYMBOL -> ENSEMBL IDs
ensembl_ids <- mapIds(
    org.Hs.eg.db,
    keys = gene_symbols,
    keytype = "SYMBOL",
    column = "ENSEMBL",
    ifnotfound = NA,
    multiVals = "first"  # take the first match if multiple
)
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
# 4. Add gene symbols as last column
res.df$sigs.df.annot <- gene_symbols

# 5. Remove rows with missing ENSEMBL IDs
valid_idx <- !is.na(ensembl_ids)
res.df <- res.df[valid_idx, ]
ensembl_ids <- ensembl_ids[valid_idx]

# 6. Remove duplicate ENSEMBL IDs (keep the first occurrence)
unique_idx <- !duplicated(ensembl_ids)
res.df <- res.df[unique_idx, ]
ensembl_ids <- ensembl_ids[unique_idx]

# 7. Set ENSEMBL IDs as rownames
rownames(res.df) <- ensembl_ids

# 8. Remove ENSEMBL column if present
res.df$Ensembl_ID <- NULL

# 9. Save CSV
output_file <- "/Users/dr.parul/Downloads/assignment files/Data needed for the assignment-20251125/DE_TumourVSNormal_Paired_results_wGeneSymbol.csv"
write.csv(res.df, file = output_file)

cat("\n*** SUCCESS: File created with unique ENSEMBL rownames and sigs.df.annot column at:\n",
    normalizePath(output_file, mustWork = FALSE), "\n***\n")

  1. Perform GSEA analysis against C5 GP BP gene sets (use the gene set file provided in RNA-seq practical) and list the top 10 mostly differentially regulated BP gene sets (based on adjusted p-values) with all the statistics listed in one table.
## Answer 4
# GSEA Analysis using Gene Symbols
# Top 10 mostly differentially regulated GO Biological Process gene sets
# Ranked by adjusted p-value (padj)

library(fgsea)
library(qusage)
library(BiocParallel)

# Force single-threaded execution to avoid port errors
register(SerialParam())

#  Load GO BP gene set file 
gmt.file <- read.gmt(
  "/Users/dr.parul/Downloads/assignment files/Data needed for the assignment-20251125/c5.go.bp.v7.4.symbols.gmt"
)

# Create ranked gene list from DESeq2 results 
# Order genes by log2 fold change (descending)
res.df.ranked <- res.df[order(res.df$log2FoldChange, decreasing = TRUE), ]

# Create named vector: names = GeneSymbol, values = log2FoldChange
DE.ranks <- setNames(res.df.ranked$log2FoldChange,
                     res.df.ranked$GeneSymbol)

# Remove NA gene symbols and duplicates
DE.ranks <- DE.ranks[!is.na(names(DE.ranks))]
DE.ranks <- DE.ranks[!duplicated(names(DE.ranks))]

# Sanity check
cat("Number of genes in ranked list:", length(DE.ranks), "\n")
## Number of genes in ranked list: 12403
cat("Top 5 upregulated genes:\n")
## Top 5 upregulated genes:
print(head(DE.ranks, 5))
##    MMP10   SPINK6    CNGB1      OSM    MMP13 
## 9.252084 7.780349 7.156698 6.903634 6.525303
cat("Top 5 downregulated genes:\n")
## Top 5 downregulated genes:
print(tail(DE.ranks, 5))
##    PRUNE2     CNTFR     ITIH5   SLC24A5   ANGPTL5 
## -7.351654 -7.651132 -7.686442 -8.020092 -8.782138
# 3. Run fgsea 
set.seed(42)

fgseaRes <- fgseaMultilevel(
  pathways = gmt.file,
  stats    = DE.ranks,
  minSize  = 15,
  maxSize  = 500
)
## Warning in fgseaMultilevel(pathways = gmt.file, stats = DE.ranks, minSize = 15,
## : There were 37 pathways for which P-values were not calculated properly due to
## unbalanced (positive and negative) gene-level statistic values. For such
## pathways pval, padj, NES, log2err are set to NA. You can try to increase the
## value of the argument nPermSimple (for example set it nPermSimple = 10000)
## Warning in fgseaMultilevel(pathways = gmt.file, stats = DE.ranks, minSize = 15,
## : For some of the pathways the P-values were likely overestimated. For such
## pathways log2err is set to NA.
# 4. Filter and rank results by adjusted p-value 
cat("\n--- fgsea completed ---\n")
## 
## --- fgsea completed ---
cat("Total pathways tested:", nrow(fgseaRes), "\n")
## Total pathways tested: 3394
cat("Significant pathways (padj < 0.05):",
    sum(fgseaRes$padj < 0.05, na.rm = TRUE), "\n")
## Significant pathways (padj < 0.05): 90
# KEEP ONLY statistically significant pathways
fgseaRes <- fgseaRes[!is.na(fgseaRes$padj) & fgseaRes$padj < 0.05, ]

# Order by adjusted p-value
fgseaRes <- fgseaRes[order(fgseaRes$padj), ]

cat("\nTop 10 mostly differentially regulated BP gene sets:\n")

# Identify Top 2 Upregulated and Top 2 Downregulated Pathways


# Separate by NES direction
upPathways <- fgseaRes[fgseaRes$NES > 0, ]
downPathways <- fgseaRes[fgseaRes$NES < 0, ]

# Order each by adjusted p-value
upPathways <- upPathways[order(upPathways$padj), ]
downPathways <- downPathways[order(downPathways$padj), ]

# Extract top 2 pathways from each
top2_up <- head(upPathways$pathway, 2)
top2_down <- head(downPathways$pathway, 2)

# Check the names
cat("Top 2 Upregulated BP gene sets:\n")

# Separate by NES direction
upPathways <- fgseaRes[fgseaRes$NES > 0, ]
downPathways <- fgseaRes[fgseaRes$NES < 0, ]

# Remove NA padj
upPathways <- upPathways[!is.na(upPathways$padj), ]
downPathways <- downPathways[!is.na(downPathways$padj), ]

# Order by padj (with NES as tie-breaker)
upPathways <- upPathways[order(upPathways$padj, -abs(upPathways$NES)), ]
downPathways <- downPathways[order(downPathways$padj, -abs(downPathways$NES)), ]

# Display top 4
